##reading in data

sagebrush <- read.table("http://users.stat.umn.edu/~gary/book/fcdae.data/pr8.7", 
                        header=TRUE, colClasses = c("factor", "factor", "numeric"))

##Creating an interaction plot

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(sagebrush, aes(x = storage, y = y, color = hum)) + geom_point() + 
  stat_summary(fun = mean, geom = "line", aes(group = hum)) + theme_bw()

##Looking at the interaction plot we see that the lines are not parallel which tells us that there is some kind of interaction. We see that humidity 1 and 2 which are the two lowest amount of humidity at 0 and 30 have the highest amount of seeds that sprout because they are low humidity. we then see that as the humidity rises to 45 percent the percent of seeds sprouting decreases dramatically the longer they are kept in storage. I am very confident that there is some kind of interaction because the lines don’t cross and are not parallel.

##The humidity does seem to change the effect of longer storage times on seed viability. Looking at humidity 1 and 2 which are 0 and 30 percent humidity we see that the percent of seed viability barely goes below 80 percent all the way to level 7 storage, which is 360 days. Then when we look at humidity 3 which is 45 percent humidity and we see that the longer the seed stays in storage the percent of viability decreases everyday.

##creating a two-way analysis

fit = aov(y ~ hum * storage, data= sagebrush)

##running qqplot

library(car)
## Loading required package: carData
qqPlot(fit, distribution = "norm")

## [1] 26 49

##Looking at the qqplot i would say that the normality assumption is not violated because all the points are between the blue bounds and follow the best fit line very well. Majority of the points are towards the upper half of the best fit line with one outlier close to the bottom and one outlier at the highest point of the graph, but these outliers are still inside the bounds.

##Running Tukey-Anscombe plot For Transformation

plot(fit, which = 1, add.smooth = FALSE)

##Looking at the Tukey plot each value shares a point between -2 and -4, but majority of the points are up and down the fitted value of 80. This makes sense because humidity 1 and 2 stay around 80 percent viability, this also makes sense that majority of the points on the qqplot are toward the upper half of the graph. Based on the Tukey plot I would say that the constant variance assumption is not violated because a common residual is shared.

##exploring possible transformations

library(MASS)
boxcox(fit)

##Looking at the boxcox plot we see that the lambda is about 1.4 because it’s between 1 and 2. We also have a confidence interval of about 0.8 and 2 and this indicates a 95 percent confidence that this is the correct lambda. Based on the lambda being within the confidence interval and the confidence we have that the lambda is correct we do not need to perform a transformation.

##summarizing the ANOVA table

summary(fit)
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## hum          2  11476    5738 1178.93 <2e-16 ***
## storage      6   1789     298   61.25 <2e-16 ***
## hum:storage 12   4154     346   71.12 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   42    204       5                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

##In the two-way ANOVA table the terms that are necessary are the p-value and f-value from the humidity*storage. The p-value of the interaction coefficient is less that 2e^-16 which is very small meaning that it’s highly significant, this means that humidity and storage do have some kind of interaction. Since the p-value is smaller than 0.05 we would reject the null hypothesis that says that humidity and storage do have some kind of effect on one another. Rejecting the null hypothesis does not make sense though because as we saw in our interaction plot, humidity and storage do have an effect on one another.
